text=(:nogroupheader:)%0a(:Summary::)%0a(:Published::)%0a(:Author:[[~GiverofMemory]]:)%0a(:License:[[https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Res_communis|Site License]]:)%0a(:Update::)%0a(:Maintainer:[[~GiverofMemory]]:)%0a(:Creator:[[]]:)%0a(:Categories:[[!]] [[!]] [[!]] [[!]]:)%0a(:Also:none:)%0a(:Archive:[[|Archive.is]], [[|Archive.org]]:)%0a(:Download:[[{$FullName}?action=print|URL]],[[https://www.web2pdfconvert.com/|PDF from URL]]:)%0a(:Redirect: Replace this text with desired PageName and delete the colon after "Redirect":)%0a%0aSee also [[WasteOil#clay]], [[brick]], [[hydrolysis]]%0a%0acan be used for sugar/hemicellulose hydrolysis [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]] basically since the clay is acidic.%0a%0aanalogue in naturally occurring bleaching earths [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]]%0a%0aWorks with [[hydrochloric acid]], [[sulfuric acid]], [[phosphoric acid]], [[nitric acid]], basically any strong acid and glacial [[acetic acid]] works a bit but not as good. [[Oxalic acid]] works great [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]]. Basically you add high concentration acid to dry clay powder and cook as hot as possible as long as possible.  Then wash very thoroughly. it may be possible to overactivate the clay [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]]%0a%0aBasically acid washed [[clay]] [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]]%0a%0aFullers earth used for cleaning clothes or [[sheep#wool]] wool [[https://sciencing.com/uses-gypsum-powder-6395376.html|#]]%0a%0aIn clays layers of silicate (si4) and aluminate (al3) are bonded together by ions of iron3, magnesium2, calcium, and aluminum3. Acid activation destroys these bonds leaving the silicate and aluminate to be loosely associated increasing surface area for binding [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]].  Not exactly sure why this makes the clay settle faster in water.  So it removes the cations causing more of a negative charge, which makes it bind to contaminants better.  This sounds similar to activating [[activated charcoal]].  Acid activation reduces the distance between layers, so it makes it more compact, perhaps explaining why it settles faster in water [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]].  also increases surface acidity, which means it would be more reactive with alkali like [[calcium oxide]] in cement like compositions.  Also from removing contaminants from [[waste oil]] for example acids work so that can help explain why activated clay works.  Acid activation produces amorphous silica, which is potentially good for certain uses.  Actually the activation renders the hydrophilic clay hydrophobic [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]], leading it to settle better.%0a%0aFor using a fired clay ([[brick]] waste) starting material, alkali activation is best [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]]%0a%0asmectite and not kaolinite or quartz are effected by the acid activation [[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169131716301946|#]] A decrease in the Al2O3, MgO, Fe2O3, and Na2O contents accompanied a relative increase in SiO2. vermiculites should also work.  Actually Acid treatment of non-swelling clay minerals like illites, kaolinites or fibrous clay minerals (sepiolite and palygorskite) has been a widely studied for improving their surface and catalytic properties - so they all should work to a degree.%0a%0aused to remove contaminants like surfactants and additives from kerosene, diesel, and other fuel oils [[http://jaxonfiltration.com/|#]]
